HOUSE JOINT RESOLUTION 1015
By Reneau
A RESOLUTION to commemorate the 250th anniversary of the
founding of the United States of America.
WHEREAS, July 4, 2026, marks the 250th anniversary, or semiquincentennial, of the
adoption of the Declaration of Independence by the Second Continental Congress in
Philadelphia in 1776, signifying the founding of the United States of America; and
WHEREAS, the Declaration of Independence proclaimed timeless principles that remain
central to the American experiment in self-government, including that all people are created
equal, all people are endowed with certain unalienable rights, and governments derive their just
powers from the consent of the governed; and
WHEREAS, the founding of the United States established a constitutional system
grounded in liberty, federalism, separation of powers, and the rule of law—principles designed
to protect individual freedom while ensuring accountable government; and
WHEREAS, throughout two and a half centuries, the American people have continued
striving to form "a more perfect Union," advancing the promise of liberty through sacrifice,
service, civic participation, and commitment to constitutional principles; and
WHEREAS, the State of Tennessee and its citizens have contributed immeasurably to
the strength, character, defense, and prosperity of the United States through their leadership,
innovation, military service, and dedication to community and country; and
WHEREAS, the semiquincentennial offers a historic opportunity for reflection, gratitude,
education, and renewed commitment to the ideals upon which this nation was founded; and
WHEREAS, commemorative activities across this State can foster civic understanding,
strengthen community bonds, inspire patriotism, and encourage thoughtful engagement with our
shared history and future; now, therefore,
HJR1015
013864
- 1 -

BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE SENATE
CONCURRING, that this General Assembly commemorates the 250th anniversary of the
founding of the United States of America.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that this General Assembly honors citizens, communities,
civic organizations, educational institutions, and businesses throughout this State that
participate in commemorative observances honoring our nation's history and celebrating the
enduring principles of liberty, equality, and self-government.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that this General Assembly praises schools and
educational institutions that provide strong civics education so that future generations
understand the rights, responsibilities, and institutions of American constitutional government,
recognizing that an informed citizenry is essential to the preservation of freedom.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that the commemoration of the United States of
America's 250th anniversary is not only a remembrance of the past but an opportunity to renew
our collective commitment to upholding the founding ideals of this nation for generations yet to
come.
